      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/qoi-relevance-direct-nih-absolute",
      "rationale": "The primary quantity of interest (QoI) is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) in g/100L, which is the directly regulated clinical endpoint for VAD hemolysis acceptance. The CFD model directly outputs NIH via integration of the power-law hemolysis damage accumulation along Lagrangian particle tracks, matching the experimental measurement protocol exactly. No surrogate QoIs are used; no indirect proxy mapping is required. The QoI is identical in simulation and experiment, maximizing relevance. Absolute threshold comparison (not relative to predicate) is enforced per COU2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
      "achievedLevel": 5,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/synth/criteria/validation-relevance-same-geometry-fluid-regime",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry used in the COU2 clinical simulations, with the same blood analog fluid, the same 5 operating points, and the same measurement protocol. Reynolds number range (Re 3,200–18,400) and specific speed (Ns 1,450–2,100 RPM·(gpm)^0.5/ft^0.75) match COU2 operating envelope exactly. No geometric scaling, fluid substitution, or operating-point extrapolation is required. Validation domain fully encloses the COU2 prediction domain, satisfying the highest relevance gradation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 5,
